Supplementary materials to the paper “Machine learning prediction models for donor Hb deferral: can we use the same models across countries?”

To evaluate the behaviour of prediction models for donor deferral we simulated an artificial donor population with mean Hb level of 9.40 and a Sd of 0.70 mmol/L. We also presumed that the Hb level of donors would be measured with a measurement error with a standard deviation of 0.50 mmol/L (without any bias).

This population has a deferral rate of 3.00%. This will lead to an observed proportion of 3.10% of measurements below the deferral threshold (see Figure 1). In case the measurement variation would be only half as big (0.25 mmol/L) there would still be a deferral rate of 1.95%.

Model fitting

We simulated a dataset of 10000 donations from the above population of which the Hb levels were measured with a standard deviation of 0 mmol/L where we did two subsequent measurements. A random forest model was trained on 80% of the data to predict donor deferral on the second Hb measurement using the Hb levels from the first measurement as a predictor. The quality of the deferral prediction model was expressed as the Corrected Area Under the Precision Recall curve (cAUPR) and as the area under the Receiver Operating Characteristic curve (AUROC) which were derived from applying the model to a test data set consisting of the remaining 20% of the data. The correction applied for the AUPR estimates consists of a subtraction of the overall deferral rate, as reported earlier (Vinkenoog et al. (2023)).

Figure 2 shows the (uncorrected) precision recall curve and Figure 3 the ROC curve for a training and test dataset.

Results

We repeated the simulation procedure 300 times for various deferral rates (1, 2, 4, 8, 16%) as shown in Figure 4. Deferral rates were set by adjusting the mean population Hb levels accordingly. Figure 5 and Figure 8 show the cAUPR and AUROC estimates for RF models trained and tested at various deferral rates. These figures clearly show that both the cAUPR and AUROC estimates increase with an increase in donor deferral rate. Also, these figures show that the cAUPR is more sensitive to changes between the models tested at various deferral rates. This is because the AUPR is sensitive changes in the positive predictive value (or precision) of the model whereas the AUROC is not. This is the main reason that AUPR performance measures are recommended for evaluating models with unbalanced binary class outcomes (Saito and Rehmsmeier (2015)). In Figure 6 the AUPR estimates for RF models for various deferral rates are shown again, but now the results for models trained at all deferral rate levels applied to all deferral rate test data are shown as well. These results are provided in numerical form in Table 1. Figure 9 and Table 2 provide the same information for AUROC estimates. From Figure 6 and Figure 9 it can be found that models trained on data sets with higher deferral rates generally have a (slightly) better performance than model trained on dataset with lower deferral rates. Figure 7 and Figure 10 show the result of applying these models to test datasets with a lower measurement error (0.25 instead of 0.50 mmol/L) but identical preset deferral rates. These figures clearly show the increase in performance of the prediction models when measurements are more accurate. The data presented in these figures is also provided in Table 1 and Table 2.

  for (i in 1:lp){
    for (j in 1:lp){
      eval(parse(text=paste0("auMean",l,"[i,j]<-mean(tedao    [,i,j,",l,",auind])")))
